===Noun===
{{en-noun|~|xiphopagi}}
# {{lb|en|countable}} Either of a pair of [[congenitally]] [[joined]] [[twin]]s (''[[Siamese twin]]'') [[united]] at the [[xiphoid process]].
#* {{quote-book|en|title=A Text-book of Pathological Anatomy and Pathogenesis|author=Ernst Ziegler|year=1885|passage='''''Xiphopagi''''' are those in which the ensiform processes are united by a cartilaginous bridge. The peritoneum passes for some distance into the connecting structure (the well-known Siamese twins were '''xiphopagi''').|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OglQAAAAYAAJ&dq=%22xiphopagi%22&pg=PA33#v=onepage&q=%22xiphopagi%22&f=false}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|journal=The Philadelphia Medical Journal|passage=Dr. Chapot-Prevost, who successfully operated upon the only other living '''xiphopagus''', has just published a report of his examination of the new living Chinese twins, Liou-Tang-Sen and Liou-Seng-Sen.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xM81AQAAMAAJ&dq=%22xiphopagus%22&pg=PA832#v=onepage&q=%22xiphopagus%22&f=false|page=832|date=May 4 1901|title=The New Living "Siamese" Twins}}
#* {{quote-book|en|title=A Clinical manual of the malformations and congenital diseases of the foetus|author=|Richard Birnbaum|year=2012|passage=In the case of a '''xiphopagus''', there is most commonly only a band-like union in the region of the xiphoid process of the sternum.}}
# {{lb|en|uncountable}} The condition of being such a twin.
#* {{quote-journal|en|journal=The Medical and Surgical Reporter|volume=68|page=28|passage=They were born in the East Indies, and make the eighth case of '''xiphopagus''' reported.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=O4k6AQAAMAAJ&dq=%22xiphopagus%22&pg=PA28#v=onepage&q=%22xiphopagus%22&f=false|title=A Case of Living Xiphopagus|year=1893}}
#* {{quote-book|en|title=Fetology: Diagnosis and Management of the Fetal Patient|author=Diana Bianchi|year=2010|passage=The common twin types include thoracopagus, '''xiphopagus''' or omphalopagus, pygopagus, ischiopagus, and craniopagus.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|title=Pediatric Anesthesia: Basic Principles, State of the Art, Future|author=Bruno Bissonnette|year=2011|passage=Thoracopagus is the most common type of conjoined twinning and, along with omphalopagus/'''xiphopagus''', represents about 75% of reported cases.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RYe4GBD6LrQC&lpg=PA1517&dq=%22xiphopagus%22&pg=PA1517#v=onepage&q=%22xiphopagus%22&f=false}}
